<TITLE> Dhaka University teems with thousands on Independence Day </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 26 (bdnews24.com)The stretch of the road from Dhaka University to the Central Shaheed Minar was abuzz with people from a broader spectrum of society on Independence Day. Ballads of heroic deeds during the Liberation War were sung Wednesday at different functions where campaigners demanded the trial of 'war criminals'. In the morning, a documentary film "Nine Months to Freedom" was screened at the Public Library auditorium for five times. Peoplefrom children to the elderlybecame emotional after watching the documentary film, based on a story by Sukdev and subtitled by Tanveer Mokammel. The documentary portrayed destroyed human habitats, oath-taking of Bangladesh government in exile, homecoming of independence leader Sheikh Mujibur Rahman and interviews with foreign journalists. The Institute of Fine Arts held a painting competition for children. Children of different ages put their brushes on the palette portraying the landscape of Bangladesh and the Liberation War using all their skills. The guardians accompanied them to the venue. Zahir Raihan's film "Stop Genocide", Babul Chowdhury's "Innocent Millions" and Layer Lavin's "Joy Bangla" were screened at Dhaka University Teacher-Student Centre. Besides, Sammilito Sangskritik Jote staged "Rajakarer Angti" at the Central Shaheed Minar. When the street drama was being staged with several thousand people in attendance, demand for the trial of the "war criminals" was raised several times. Discussion programmes and cultural programmes were held at the Shilpakala Academy and the Bangla Academy. Large numbers of children and juveniles also thronged the Shishu Park. bdnews24
